<section xml:id="chapter1-3" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>The Distance Formula</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
    Now that we know how to plot points on the coordinate plane, it is natural to ask how far apart two points are.
    There are various ways to measure the distance between two points, and in this course, we are talking about the shortest distance between two points. 
    The shortest distance between two points is given by the Distance Formula. 
    In this section, we will provide a proof of the Distance Formula and use the formula to solve various mathematical and applied problems.
  </p>
  </introduction>
  <subsection xml:id="sub-distances-in-the-real-world">
    <title>Distances in the Real World</title>
    
<p>
    In the real world, people can't walk through objects; therefore, taking the shortest path between two points is often impossible.
    Traveling in a town or city is an example of this. Many neighborhoods are laid out in a square grid, and people can only travel
    along the roads which act as the sides of the squares. For example, in the following image, if a person wants to travel from point
    <m>A</m> to point <m>B</m>, they can travel two blocks east and one block north. The total distance traveled is three city blocks.
    This measure of distance is called the <term>Taxicab Metric</term> since it measures the distance a taxicab takes as it takes
    a passenger from point <m>A</m> to point <m>B</m>.
  </p>
<figure xml:id="graph-taxicab-metric">
    <caption>A grid of city blocks with a red line showing the path of a taxicab from point <m>A</m> to point <m>B</m>.</caption>
    <image source="chapter-1-3/taxicab_v1.png" width="50%">
      <shortdescription>
        The taxicab travels two blocks east, turns north, and travels an additional block.
      </shortdescription>    
    </image>
</figure>
<p>
   There are a couple problems with the Taxicab Metric.
   <ul>
    <li>
<p>
    In mathematics, we often want important concepts to be unique.
    In the Taxicab Metric, the shortest distance is not unique—there are three ways to travel from <m>A</m> to <m>B</m> in 3 city blocks.
  </p>
</li>
    <li>
  <p>
    The three ways to get from <m>A</m> to <m>B</m> in 3 city blocks.
  </p>
    </li>
</ul>
</p>
<figure xml:id="graph-taxicab-metric-multiple-paths">
    <caption>The three minimum-length paths the taxicab can take.</caption>
    <sidebyside>
        <figure xml:id="graph-taxicab-metric-path1">
            <caption>The taxicab travels two blocks east, then turns north.</caption>
            <image source="chapter-1-3/taxicab_v1.png" width="40%" decorative="yes">   
