</figure>

<figure xml:id="graph-distance-formula-line-segment">
    <caption>
      The shortest distance between points <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> is the length of the line segment joining them.
    </caption>
    <image source="chapter-1-3/taxicab_v4.png" width="50%">
        <shortdescription>
            A red, dashed line segment connects points A and B.
        </shortdescription>
    </image>
  </figure>

<p>
    However, the idea of traveling via city blocks does give us enough information to find the shortest distance between <m>A</m> and <m>B</m>.
    If we call the intersection where the taxi turns left point <m>C</m>, then the points <m>A</m>, <m>B</m>, and <m>C</m> form the right triangle <m>\triangle ABC</m>.
    This means that side <m>b</m> has length 2 and side <m>a</m> has length 1.
  </p>

  <figure>
    <caption>When we combine <xref ref="graph-taxicab-metric"/> with <xref ref="graph-distance-formula-line-segment"/>, we get a right triangle.</caption>
    <image source="chapter-1-3/taxicab_v5.png" width="50%">
    <shortdescription>Right triangle formed by points A, B, and C on a city grid.</shortdescription>
    </image>
  </figure>

 <p>
    Since we have a right triangle, we can use the Pythagorean Theorem to solve for side <m>c</m> — the shortest distance from <m>A</m> to <m>B</m>:
    <md>
      <mrow>a^2 + b^2 \amp = c^2</mrow>
      <mrow>1^2 + 2^2 \amp = c^2</mrow>
      <mrow>1 + 4 \amp = c^2</mrow>
      <mrow>5 \amp = c^2</mrow>
      <mrow>\sqrt{5} \amp = c</mrow>
      <mrow>2.236 \amp \approx c</mrow>
    </md>
    Therefore, the shortest distance from <m>A</m> to <m>B</m> is approximately 2.236 city blocks.
  </p>

  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="sub-distance-formula">
    <title>Proof of the Distance Formula</title>
    <theorem xml:id="thm-distance-formula">
      <title>The Distance Formula</title>
      <statement>

  <p>
    Let <m>A = (x_1, y_1)</m> and <m>B = (x_2, y_2)</m> be any two points on the coordinate plane.
    The distance <m>d</m> between <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> is given by the formula
    <me>d = \sqrt{(x_2 - x_1)^2 + (y_2 - y_1)^2}</me>
  </p>

  <figure>
    <caption>
      Points <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> with a dashed line segment connecting them. The dashed line segment is labeled with the Distance Formula.
    </caption>
    <image source="chapter-1-3/distance_formula.png" width="50%">
    <shortdescription>
      Diagram showing a dashed line joining points A and B. The line is labeled with the Distance Formula.
    </shortdescription>
  </image>
  </figure>
      </statement>
      <proof>
  <p>
    It turns out that the Pythagorean Theorem is the key to finding a general formula for the Distance Formula.
    We are still traveling from point <m>A = (x_1, y_1)</m> to point <m>B = (x_2, y_2)</m>.
    If we draw a horizontal line through <m>A</m> and a vertical line through point <m>B</m>,
    the intersection of the horizontal line and vertical line is the point <m>C = (x_2, y_1)</m>.
    The points <m>A</m>, <m>B</m>, and <m>C</m> also form the right triangle <m>\triangle ABC</m>.
  </p>

  <figure xml:id="graph-distance-formula-right-triangle"> <caption><m>\triangle ABC</m> formed by connecting the points <m>A</m>, <m>B</m>, and <m>C</m>.</caption>
    <image source="chapter-1-3/right_triangle.png" width="50%">
    <shortdescription>Right triangle formed by connecting points A, B, and C.</shortdescription>
    </image>
  </figure>

  <p>
    To use the Pythagorean Theorem, we need to measure sides <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> of <m>\triangle ABC</m>.
    Fortunately, distances on vertical and horizontal lines are equivalent to finding distances on a number line.
    Since the points <m>A</m> and <m>C</m> are on the same horizontal line, to find the length of side <m>b</m>,
    we find the difference of their first coordinates: <m>b = |x_2 - x_1|</m>.
    Since the points <m>B</m> and <m>C</m> are on the same vertical line, to find the length of side <m>a</m>,
    we find the difference of their second coordinates: <m>a = |y_2 - y_1|</m>.
  </p>

  <figure><caption> <xref ref="graph-distance-formula-right-triangle"/> with the formulas <m>a = |y_2 - y_1|</m> and <m>b = |x_2 - x_1|</m> labeling the short and long legs, respectively.</caption>
    <image source="chapter-1-3/right_triangle_V2.png" width="50%">
    <shortdescription>Right triangle with legs labeled using coordinate differences.</shortdescription>
    </image>
  </figure>

  <p>
    Now, we have all the information required to compute the distance from <m>A</m> to <m>B</m>.
    The following calculation shows us how to compute the distance for any two points:
  </p>

  <p>
    <md>
      <mrow>c^2 \amp = a^2 + b^2</mrow>
      <mrow>c^2 \amp = |x_2 - x_1|^2 + |y_2 - y_1|^2</mrow>
      <mrow>c^2 \amp = (x_2 - x_1)^2 + (y_2 - y_1)^2</mrow>
      <mrow>c \amp = \sqrt{(x_2 - x_1)^2 + (y_2 - y_1)^2}</mrow>
    </md>
  </p>

  <p>
    Instead of drawing a picture and using the Pythagorean Theorem every time we have to compute a distance,
    we can use the final line of the previous calculation to compute the distance directly.
    Since we are calculating a distance, we will use the letter <m>d</m> instead of <m>c</m> in the formula.
  </p>
      </proof>
    </theorem>
    <note>
    <p>
      In a problem, it doesn't matter which point you call <m>A</m> and which you call <m>B</m> since
      <m>(x_1 - x_2)^2 = (x_2 - x_1)^2</m> and <m>(y_1 - y_2)^2 = (y_2 - y_1)^2</m>.
    </p>
  </note>
    
  </subsection>
